WEBVTT

00:00.130 --> 00:03.195
Thank you for downloading or streaming this message from Immanuel Church.

00:03.616 --> 00:08.124
We are one church with multiple locations, and we believe God wants to bless you right where you are.

00:08.705 --> 00:14.275
In a few moments, you're going to hear some practical teaching from God's Word that I believe will be inspiring and relevant to your life.

00:15.036 --> 00:24.914
First though, if you haven't yet experienced Immanuel Live, we encourage you to go to our website eclife.org to check out our service times and locations so that you can experience Immanuel in person

00:24.994 --> 00:26.235
or through our online campus.

00:26.936 --> 00:35.705
If this message blesses you and you'd like to support the ministry financially, again, you can go to eclive.org and click on the giving tab and choose online campus at your campus.

00:36.366 --> 00:40.871
Thanks again for joining us today and we hope this message will be an encouragement to you on your spiritual journey.

00:41.952 --> 00:50.962
I really love that second song that we play because it's so beautiful and the words are so powerful and people get into it, but there's that part where it dips and people start clapping and then they realize it's still going.

00:51.262 --> 00:53.665
They're like, oh, I got to dance out of this one because I'm still going.

00:53.925 --> 00:54.866
We're still praising.

00:55.362 --> 00:57.825
And you can hear it like I'm in the front row, and I can hear it.

00:58.206 --> 01:00.589
And I know you guys are doing it in the background, because I did it yesterday.

01:00.609 --> 01:02.592
I was just like, oh, not it, not the right time.

01:02.652 --> 01:04.775
But hey, thank you for coming out.

01:04.855 --> 01:05.556
Really appreciate it.

01:05.596 --> 01:07.919
How many of you have already put your Christmas decorations away?

01:08.620 --> 01:09.401
You monsters.

01:12.145 --> 01:13.506
My wife is the exact same way, though.

01:13.526 --> 01:14.728
She gets so hyped for Christmas.

01:14.768 --> 01:15.910
She gets so up for it.

01:15.930 --> 01:16.531
We drive around.

01:16.551 --> 01:17.211
We go downtown.

01:17.252 --> 01:17.892
We look at the lights.

01:17.912 --> 01:18.573
We go to the circle.

01:18.593 --> 01:21.297
And then at 12 on 1 on December 26, we're out.

01:21.677 --> 01:22.418
Put it to the shed.

01:22.779 --> 01:23.200
Bury it.

01:23.340 --> 01:23.640
Kill it.

01:23.720 --> 01:24.481
Christmas is dead.

01:24.621 --> 01:25.042
We're out.

01:25.826 --> 01:27.628
So I'm glad to know she's not the only one that does that.

01:27.648 --> 01:29.289
I hope that you had a very Merry Christmas.

01:29.669 --> 01:32.292
I hope you had an amazing time with your family and your kids.

01:32.352 --> 01:35.675
I hope you ate your bite, your body weight, and spiral sliced ham.

01:35.955 --> 01:37.136
I hope it was magical for you.

01:37.536 --> 01:44.402
But as we look towards the new year, I do want to caution you just a little bit to not fly into the new year quite so quickly.

01:44.522 --> 01:45.583
I should probably introduce myself.

01:45.603 --> 01:46.744
Hi, my name's Cody.

01:46.924 --> 01:49.146
I'm the campus pastor here at the Immanuel Church Greenwood campus.

01:49.547 --> 01:53.790
I would like to welcome anybody that's joining us online at our multi sites or our micro sites.

01:53.810 --> 01:55.011
Thank you so much for tuning in.

01:55.232 --> 01:55.812
Can we give it up for them?

01:55.792 --> 01:56.553
Let's give them a little clap.

01:56.894 --> 01:57.254
Yes.

02:00.879 --> 02:02.602
I'm sure you all look tremendous.

02:02.722 --> 02:09.531
Now, before we dive right into the new year, it's very easy time of year to do that, because we're thinking about our new goals and our new resolutions.

02:09.892 --> 02:17.042
We're looking in 2020, but I want us to take a second and look back, not just at this year, because we're getting ready to move out of this decade.

02:17.378 --> 02:18.439
which is crazy to think about.

02:18.459 --> 02:25.747
Some of us have been so busy, so caught up in everything that we've completely forgotten that the 2010s are coming to an end, and another decade is ending.

02:26.107 --> 02:30.532
I know that because I've talked to some of you, whether you're on staff, whether you're regular or tender as our church, you've said, you know what?

02:30.832 --> 02:31.533
You are right.

02:31.553 --> 02:33.295
The 2010s are over my goodness.

02:33.315 --> 02:33.955
Where did it go?

02:33.995 --> 02:35.737
Yes, we are ending a decade.

02:37.119 --> 02:41.123
And as we look for, I want you to think about your own life and how it went.

02:41.303 --> 02:43.986
So the question I post to you is, how did your decade go?

02:45.858 --> 02:47.379
It's fair question, it's 10 years.

02:48.340 --> 02:49.982
Did you progress in any areas?

02:50.523 --> 02:52.324
Are you happy with how the decade went?

02:52.865 --> 02:54.827
Did you regress in other areas?

02:55.467 --> 02:57.309
So maybe your spending is getting a little bit better.

02:57.770 --> 02:59.451
Maybe your parenting has gotten a little bit better.

02:59.471 --> 03:03.775
Maybe you actually had a kid this past decade or maybe your job is not going so well.

03:04.376 --> 03:06.918
Maybe things aren't going as good as you hope that they would.

03:07.699 --> 03:14.706
Because when you think about the passage of time when it comes to a decade, the average life expectancy for a man in the United States is 79 years.

03:15.074 --> 03:16.517
Ladies, you are stronger than men.

03:16.917 --> 03:17.879
You're wiser than men.

03:17.899 --> 03:18.841
You're smarter than men.

03:19.262 --> 03:19.923
You're faster.

03:19.983 --> 03:20.985
You're survivors.

03:21.065 --> 03:23.449
Your average life expectancy is actually two more years.

03:23.469 --> 03:24.892
You live to be 81 years of age.

03:24.912 --> 03:26.695
So let's give it up for the ladies in the house today.

03:29.320 --> 03:30.642
He's like, yes, praise him.

03:32.258 --> 03:34.563
Now I'm going to get on you ladies and saying, I'm a little upset with you.

03:34.583 --> 03:36.407
I'm going to tell you why in just a little bit.

03:36.487 --> 03:42.319
But when you think about what a decade represents in your life expectancy for men, it's about 12.6% of your life.

03:42.740 --> 03:44.885
For women, it's about 12.3% of your life.

03:44.905 --> 03:51.939
So if you average it out, about 12.5% of your life has just passed you by in the past decade.

03:51.959 --> 03:53.202
How crazy is that?

03:54.146 --> 03:58.651
When you think about all these things that have happened, there have been so many different things that have happened in the past 10 years.

03:58.691 --> 04:00.933
Now, I get to share with you some of those things.

04:01.354 --> 04:03.036
And I'm really excited because, yeah, I have props.

04:03.096 --> 04:04.137
Normally, I don't have props.

04:04.157 --> 04:04.998
I don't have stuff to use.

04:05.018 --> 04:06.519
So this is like a very exciting thing for me.

04:07.620 --> 04:11.084
But you think about the past 10 years and all of the things that have happened, all of the things that have changed.

04:11.104 --> 04:12.586
You think about smartphones.

04:12.646 --> 04:14.027
This is an iPhone 3.

04:14.087 --> 04:16.710
This is what iPhones looked like 10 years ago.

04:17.131 --> 04:18.232
Look how small this thing is.

04:18.272 --> 04:20.274
How are you supposed to answer any emails on this thing?

04:20.930 --> 04:21.631
It gets awful.

04:21.851 --> 04:24.114
Now they're like as big as the top of my finger.

04:24.154 --> 04:26.116
Like, geez Louise, it's so tiny.

04:26.557 --> 04:29.601
I don't know if you're like me, but 10 years ago, I was still in college.

04:29.621 --> 04:31.103
I actually didn't have a smartphone yet.

04:31.143 --> 04:33.345
I had a flip phone and I had one of these bad boys.

04:33.365 --> 04:34.967
You know what's inside this puffy black case?

04:35.588 --> 04:36.669
It's a digital camera.

04:37.450 --> 04:46.962
I was searching through my closet and I actually still had my digital camera from college, which includes a wrist strap because Kodak didn't trust me enough to take a picture without spiking it on the ground.

04:48.258 --> 04:51.722
Do you know how long it took to upload a photo from one of these to Facebook?

04:51.742 --> 04:52.703
Roughly seven hours.

04:54.765 --> 05:00.191
So if you look at my Facebook and you're like, man, he only had like two pictures back in 2000, geez, back in 2010.

05:00.251 --> 05:02.413
It's because it didn't want to mess with this thing.

05:02.433 --> 05:03.975
And it's got the puffy case.

05:04.015 --> 05:08.200
It's got the rechargeable batteries, the memory disk, because the camera only held like one picture.

05:08.460 --> 05:10.422
There's been so much that's happened with phones.

05:10.742 --> 05:11.764
Some of you had blackberries.

05:11.824 --> 05:14.066
My fingers were always too fat for the blackberry buttons.

05:14.754 --> 05:21.263
You think about music in the past 10 years ago, people were still using CDs trying to burn the perfect CD right on the front with Sharpie.

05:21.283 --> 05:22.385
You got one opportunity.

05:22.405 --> 05:24.949
If you messed up the Sharpie, you had to burn the CD again.

05:24.969 --> 05:27.072
It was a terrible experience.

05:27.112 --> 05:28.434
I talked to a guy that was on staff.

05:28.454 --> 05:29.195
He was a younger guy.

05:29.455 --> 05:31.338
He was like, yeah, you know, I've actually never owned a CD.

05:33.000 --> 05:34.322
Are you kidding me?

05:34.530 --> 05:35.311
You've never had a seat.

05:35.331 --> 05:36.874
I've got like three in my car right now.

05:36.914 --> 05:40.299
I went home and I had a bunch of cream corn because I was a thousand years old.

05:40.320 --> 05:43.485
I felt so old after he said that.

05:43.505 --> 05:44.967
I was like, oh, I'm out of touch.

05:45.007 --> 05:45.608
I'm losing it.

05:46.309 --> 05:48.032
You think about the way that we listen to music now.

05:48.092 --> 05:49.535
Everybody has air pods.

05:49.575 --> 05:52.439
Now, some of you can't wait to lose the air pods that you got for Christmas.

05:52.459 --> 05:53.181
You're so excited.

05:53.401 --> 05:54.683
They're tiny and they fit in your ear.

05:54.984 --> 05:56.466
Look at these monstrosities.

05:57.218 --> 05:58.840
There's like leather on the padding.

05:58.860 --> 05:59.581
Look at these headphones.

05:59.601 --> 06:00.282
They're plastic.

06:00.302 --> 06:02.365
There's this giant anaconda cord.

06:02.625 --> 06:04.888
Some of you are probably thinking, I still have headphones like that.

06:05.149 --> 06:06.370
Me too, why do you think I brought them?

06:09.395 --> 06:11.477
Now ladies, here's what I'm gonna get on you just a little bit.

06:11.598 --> 06:16.584
I'm actually wearing an article of clothing that has changed significantly, especially for men in the past 10 years.

06:16.624 --> 06:18.046
I'd like you to guess what that is.

06:18.187 --> 06:19.528
Online, you can play along as well.

06:19.769 --> 06:20.810
What am I wearing this changed?

06:21.651 --> 06:22.913
Jeans, you're dog gone, right?

06:22.953 --> 06:24.075
The jeans have changed.

06:24.575 --> 06:25.316
Yes, they've changed.

06:25.336 --> 06:26.578
Why have they changed?

06:26.658 --> 06:29.381
Ten years ago, for men, jeans were very, very unforgiving.

06:29.881 --> 06:30.682
There was no flex.

06:30.702 --> 06:32.704
There was no give in the fabric of the pants.

06:32.825 --> 06:34.687
Once you were in them, you were in them, and that was it.

06:35.487 --> 06:37.029
The waistline was the waistline.

06:37.049 --> 06:37.990
There was no stretching.

06:38.030 --> 06:43.556
But now, with the introduction of flex fabric, anytime I want to hit the elevator and take it to the bottom floor, I can do it.

06:47.480 --> 06:49.082
I'm down here all day, baby.

06:49.783 --> 06:50.183
All day.

06:51.124 --> 06:51.605
You know why?

06:51.665 --> 06:55.269
Because we've got flex jeans, flex khakis, flex, whatever.

06:55.309 --> 06:56.530
And it's amazing.

06:56.674 --> 06:59.018
Ladies, why did you hold out for so long?

07:00.340 --> 07:02.865
In the Bible, it says, don't hide your light under a basket.

07:02.905 --> 07:04.788
You held it for so long.

07:05.169 --> 07:05.970
You have yoga pants.

07:05.990 --> 07:06.651
You have stretch pants.

07:06.671 --> 07:07.272
You have jaggings.

07:07.573 --> 07:09.135
You knew about this and you said nothing.

07:11.259 --> 07:12.000
But I'm going to forgive you.

07:12.020 --> 07:13.443
I'm going to take the elevator back up.

07:15.446 --> 07:16.087
But so happy.

07:16.107 --> 07:17.029
Technology is amazing.

07:17.049 --> 07:17.890
I can work out in these pants.

07:17.910 --> 07:22.418
I can do anything and conquer the world in these jeans because of the flex fabric and the change in the past decade.

07:23.010 --> 07:26.375
Like I said, I was still in college 10 years ago making some bone head decisions.

07:26.415 --> 07:27.176
I wasn't getting drunk.

07:27.236 --> 07:28.058
I wasn't getting high.

07:28.418 --> 07:29.920
I just would do dumb things.

07:30.421 --> 07:32.204
It goes on the way back from the shower one day.

07:32.244 --> 07:33.566
I'm going back to my room.

07:33.586 --> 07:34.567
My roommate broke code.

07:34.587 --> 07:35.669
He didn't leave the door cracked.

07:35.689 --> 07:36.430
He went to class.

07:36.811 --> 07:39.975
So my phone, my keys, everything is in the room.

07:40.076 --> 07:40.777
I'm locked out.

07:41.157 --> 07:42.139
The RA is gone.

07:42.179 --> 07:44.182
Everybody on the floor is gone because they're at class.

07:44.522 --> 07:45.364
They're getting breakfast.

07:45.384 --> 07:47.026
I had the late class that morning.

07:47.266 --> 07:49.308
So I'm a rule follower, and I got a choice to make now.

07:49.408 --> 08:03.842
I can either take my loss, I can either email the professor when I get back in the room, say, yeah, I got locked down, I'm gonna have to remake the quiz, or on the other side of my rule following brain, I can walk outside wearing nothing but a towel and sandals, go to campus services, get the key, unlock it, and take the quiz.

08:04.282 --> 08:08.446
So naturally, I did what any logical sane person would do, and I left my dorm half naked.

08:11.629 --> 08:16.914
When Vikings would conquer new lands, and when they would arrive on the beach,

08:17.026 --> 08:22.151
They would burn the boats so that there was no chance for them to go back and return to the land that they had left.

08:22.672 --> 08:27.277
When I left my dorm room, I burnt my boat to the ground because the door locked behind me.

08:29.479 --> 08:30.860
So we were committed at that point.

08:32.903 --> 08:39.189
So I started walking with nothing but a towel, my shower sandies, my left eye exposed, and we're just walking and I'm doing good.

08:39.229 --> 08:40.410
Everything's great.

08:40.751 --> 08:41.472
I'm half naked.

08:41.532 --> 08:43.794
Try not to get arrested for indecent exposure.

08:44.034 --> 08:45.716
And I don't see anybody.

08:45.756 --> 08:46.958
All is pretty quiet on the campus.

08:46.978 --> 08:49.722
And then out of nowhere, there's a sky that's walking towards me, one of the students.

08:49.742 --> 08:50.563
And he's looking at his phone.

08:51.064 --> 08:51.925
And I'm thinking, OK, I'm good.

08:51.945 --> 08:52.486
He doesn't see me.

08:52.506 --> 08:54.208
I'm just going to sneak around him, give him a wide berth.

08:54.428 --> 08:55.210
He totally saw me.

08:55.790 --> 08:56.692
And he was looking at his phone.

08:56.732 --> 08:58.334
And when he saw me, he didn't say a word.

08:58.414 --> 09:01.538
All he did was look me up and down and just went, oh.

09:02.940 --> 09:03.922
And then he just kept going.

09:04.062 --> 09:05.984
And I think, OK, that's a little embarrassing.

09:06.025 --> 09:06.986
I can deal with that, whatever.

09:07.306 --> 09:08.408
So I get to campus services.

09:08.448 --> 09:09.970
I knock on the door frantically.

09:10.050 --> 09:11.451
Like, hey, help me out, help me out.

09:11.471 --> 09:13.293
This guy comes and he sees me.

09:13.313 --> 09:15.375
And he's just like, what is going on?

09:15.415 --> 09:17.237
Why are you here in a towel?

09:17.257 --> 09:18.058
He's like, can I help you?

09:18.078 --> 09:19.679
And I say, yeah, man, I'm locked out of my room.

09:19.699 --> 09:20.360
You got to help me.

09:20.540 --> 09:21.241
Like, I'm freaking out.

09:21.461 --> 09:22.662
I got a quiz in like 45 minutes.

09:22.702 --> 09:23.043
Please help me.

09:23.063 --> 09:24.204
Just take me back to the room and unlock the door.

09:24.224 --> 09:25.065
I'll never bother you again.

09:25.125 --> 09:25.425
Please.

09:26.306 --> 09:28.147
He takes his deep side because he's so annoyed.

09:28.348 --> 09:28.888
And he leaves.

09:29.509 --> 09:30.950
And I'm thinking he's going to call the police.

09:31.130 --> 09:31.771
He's going to call the dean.

09:31.791 --> 09:32.712
I'm going to get kicked out of school.

09:32.752 --> 09:33.473
Everything's terrible.

09:33.693 --> 09:34.634
He comes back with keys.

09:34.874 --> 09:39.058
And we walk back to the dorm side by side and complete silence because he hates me.

09:41.666 --> 09:46.032
So we get back to the dorm, he puts the key in, he turns it, and I'm thinking, okay, we're home free, everything's great.

09:46.533 --> 09:53.303
And right as he's about to open it, he stops, and he looks at me, and he says, what would you have done had I not been there?

09:54.124 --> 09:56.627
And I'm thinking, is this a riddle man I'm half naked, can we just go inside?

09:56.647 --> 10:00.793
And he says, what would you have done had I not been there?

10:00.953 --> 10:02.536
You would have been locked out, what would you have done?

10:03.237 --> 10:05.139
And I said, I didn't really think that far ahead.

10:06.101 --> 10:09.746
And he smirked, and he said, you don't strike me as the kind of guy that does.

10:13.250 --> 10:16.173
If you open the door, I went inside, and we never saw each other again.

10:18.656 --> 10:19.757
So that was me 10 years ago.

10:19.797 --> 10:27.146
And if you want to know how much can change in the passage of a decade, I go from being that bonehead 10 years ago to being a bonehead now who is married.

10:27.226 --> 10:28.407
She got the short end of the stick.

10:28.888 --> 10:33.012
I am now a father to two little girls, which is terrifying that I'm in charge of raising any kids.

10:33.693 --> 10:41.682
And I am now a campus pastor at one of the campuses for the 98th largest church in the United States of America, charged with the spiritual care and reformation of an entire community of people.

10:49.442 --> 10:51.705
So if you didn't know that God had a sense of humor before, now you do.

10:53.868 --> 10:55.350
And that's all fun, and that's all well and good.

10:55.370 --> 10:58.213
I'm sure you guys have stories that you can relate to, how you've changed in a decade.

10:58.233 --> 11:03.340
I can't imagine some of the crazy, fun things that you've seen and the ways that you've changed, and it's awesome.

11:03.660 --> 11:05.042
And it's good to laugh about stuff like that.

11:05.062 --> 11:17.138
But as we look back, we could probably all agree that there are some areas where we've fallen a little short, some opportunities that we maybe didn't see, some things we wish we would have done a little bit differently, different choices that we made, but we didn't quite do what we wanted to do.

11:17.698 --> 11:21.344
And here's the thing about the passage of time when it comes to a decade.

11:21.404 --> 11:25.009
Time passes and not much changes when it comes to our lives.

11:25.610 --> 11:29.877
It is our actions and habits, the choices that we make that actually change things.

11:29.917 --> 11:32.781
That's where you see the real change throughout the passage of time.

11:32.841 --> 11:33.843
Time really does nothing.

11:34.284 --> 11:36.807
Things will happen and these things and these new bits of technology will happen.

11:36.827 --> 11:42.516
But when it comes to actual real change in our life, it's about what we do, what we say, the things that we choose to engage in.

11:42.536 --> 11:46.322
I don't know if you guys had seen this, but the University of Scranton

11:46.530 --> 11:51.918
had a study where they found that 92% of people, 92% of people don't complete their goals.

11:52.379 --> 11:53.340
That's kind of heartbreaking.

11:53.921 --> 11:58.528
Like you said a goal, 92% of people are not macking it out, which is kind of hard.

11:58.548 --> 12:01.612
And that goes for New Year's resolutions, new goals, whatever, it may be 92%.

12:03.535 --> 12:07.461
And this guy Douglas Vermeerin did a study and he found they phoned all different types of categories.

12:07.781 --> 12:10.325
Like people phoned certain groups of why they didn't accomplish their goal.

12:10.746 --> 12:13.650
Maybe it's a fear of success or a fear of failure.

12:13.858 --> 12:14.819
Talk about failure a lot.

12:14.839 --> 12:15.741
Nobody wants to be embarrassed.

12:15.761 --> 12:16.762
Somebody wants to fall short.

12:17.283 --> 12:22.671
But fear of success is a little bit different because now once you succeed a little bit, now there's more pressure, now there's more expectation.

12:22.711 --> 12:23.973
People expect more out of you.

12:24.334 --> 12:25.536
And some people are afraid of that.

12:25.556 --> 12:26.117
They don't want that.

12:26.137 --> 12:28.260
They just want to kind of fly under the radar and do their own thing.

12:28.921 --> 12:30.563
Some people have a lack of know-how.

12:30.603 --> 12:32.466
They don't know how to get to where they want to go.

12:32.827 --> 12:37.634
They don't have the right people around them, the right resources, the right books, videos, YouTube links, whatever it may be.

12:37.654 --> 12:40.519
They don't have the information to get them from A to B.

12:41.400 --> 12:42.802
Some people lack discipline.

12:43.298 --> 12:45.542
They know what they want to do and they start off really strong.

12:45.562 --> 12:52.276
They've got a lot of intensity at the beginning, but they fizzle out because when things get tough, when things don't go their way or those little things pop up along the road, they quit.

12:52.596 --> 12:55.742
They bail because they don't have the discipline to persevere and push through.

12:55.782 --> 12:58.688
Some people lack the motivation, the desire.

12:59.209 --> 13:00.712
They just sit and they wait too long.

13:00.752 --> 13:04.519
They think, they think, they think and they never follow through, they never execute.

13:04.539 --> 13:05.842
Some people lack a plan.

13:06.370 --> 13:07.371
They're action oriented.

